      "text": "Here is the translation of the provided text, as accurately as possible.\n\n**Laws of the Maldives**\n\n**Foreign Exchange Act**\n\n**Chapter One**\n**Introduction**\n\n**Introduction and Name**\n1.\n(a) This is the law to determine the transactions that can be conducted in foreign currency in the Maldives, to establish the principles regarding the deposit and exchange of foreign currency income of businesses into banks, and to state other matters related to foreign currency.\n(b) This Act shall be cited as the \"Foreign Exchange Act\".\n\n**Purpose**\n2.\nThe main purposes of this Act are stated below.\n(a) To facilitate the availability of foreign currency in the Maldives;\n(b) To determine the transactions that can be conducted in foreign currency in the Maldives, including transactions made through bank accounts;\n(c) To establish the principles regarding the deposit of foreign currency income of businesses into a bank account; and\n(d) To establish the principles regarding the conversion of a portion of foreign currency income to Rufiyaa.\n\n**Chapter Two**\n**Medium of Monetary Transactions in the Maldives**\n\n**Transactions in Rufiyaa**\n3.\n(a) Unless expressly stated otherwise in this Act or any other law, all monetary obligations or transactions in the Maldives shall be offered and settled in Rufiyaa.\n(b) With the exception of transactions expressly stated to be permissible in foreign currency in this Act or any other law, it is prohibited to offer or settle any monetary obligation or transaction in the Maldives in a foreign currency.\n\n**Transactions in Foreign Currency**\n4.\nNotwithstanding the provisions of Article 3 of this Act, the following obligations and transactions may be offered and settled in foreign currency:\n(a) The payment and acceptance of money permitted to be paid to the government or a state institution in a foreign currency, under the authority of a law or regulation;\n(b) Services provided by banks and financing companies, and transactions between such institutions and their customers;\n(c) Transactions between remittance service providers and their customers;\n(d) In relation to insurance policies sold by insurance companies to sellers of goods and providers of services in the tourism sector, transactions between such companies and their customers, and transactions between insurance intermediaries and customers in connection with such policies, and other transactions determined in the regulations made under this Act from among the transactions conducted by insurance companies;\n(e) Transactions in the securities market of the Maldives;\n(f) International transactions;\n(g) Accepting the price of goods sold to tourists and services rendered to tourists in foreign currency;\n(h) Accepting the price of exported goods and services in foreign currency;\n(i) If a business that earns income in foreign currency wishes to pay for the goods it purchases and the services it procures in foreign currency, the payment of the price in foreign currency, and the acceptance of the price in foreign currency by the party that sold the goods or provided the service;\n(j) If a business that earns income in foreign currency so desires, the payment of dividends to shareholders, and other transactions between the business and its shareholders, and transactions between such a business and other related parties;\n(k) The sale and purchase of shares of a business that earns income in foreign currency, the issuance of bonds or sukuk by such a business, and transactions between such a business and its bondholders and sukuk holders;\n(l) If a business that earns income in foreign currency so desires, the payment of salaries and benefits to its employees in foreign currency, and the acceptance of salaries and benefits by employees in foreign currency;\n(m) The acceptance of the price of goods and services sold to tourists by duty-free shops from tourists in foreign currency and the payment of that price by tourists in foreign currency;\n(n) Foreign currency obligations determined to be paid in a judgment or order of a court of law, or a decision of a tribunal, or a decision made under a dispute resolution mechanism such as arbitration;\n(o) Other obligations and transactions as determined in the regulations made under this Act.\n\n**Maldivians Not to be Compelled to Pay in Foreign Currency**\n5.\nAlthough it is stated in Article 4 of this Act that the obligations and transactions mentioned therein are permitted to be offered and settled in foreign currency, except in matters where the government, state institutions, and financial institutions have determined to transact in foreign currency in accordance with the law, no Maldivian shall be compelled to pay for goods purchased and services procured in the Maldives in a foreign currency.\n\n**Chapter Three**\n**Foreign Currency**\n\n**Foreign Currency**\n6.\n(a) For the purpose of this Act, foreign currency refers to the currency of any country other than the Maldives.\n(b) In accordance with the law, it is permissible to import foreign currency into the Maldives, export foreign currency from the Maldives, possess and use foreign currency in the Maldives, and invest in the Maldives in foreign currency.\n(c) It is permissible to open and use a foreign currency account in a bank, in a manner determined by that bank.\n\n**Chapter Four**\n**Deposit of Income Received in Foreign Currency**\n\n**Depositing Foreign Currency Income into a Bank Account**\n7.\n(a) The realized sales proceeds in foreign currency received within a calendar month for goods and services sold or provided by the following parties shall be transferred or deposited into a foreign currency account opened in a bank before the 28th (twenty-eighth) day of the third month following that month.\n(1) Sellers of goods and providers of services in the tourism sector; and\n(2) Parties, other than those mentioned in sub-paragraph (1) of paragraph (a) of this Article and financial institutions, who receive an amount equivalent to at least 15,000,000.00 (fifteen million) United States Dollars in foreign currency within the preceding calendar year for goods and services sold or provided.\n(b) The foreign currency deposited under paragraph (a) of this Article may be deposited in any foreign currency in which the depositing bank opens a foreign currency account and which is authorized by the Authority.\n\n**Provision of Information by State Institutions**\n8.\n(a) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in any other law, upon request by the Authority, MIRA shall provide the Authority with information and accounts of the parties mentioned in Article 7 of this Act to the extent necessary to achieve the objectives of this Act.\n(b) Information regarding tourist resorts, integrated tourist resorts, private islands, resort hotels, tourist vessels, tourist hotels, tourist guesthouses, and other such places registered under Law No. 2/99 (Maldives Tourism Act) at the time of commencement of this Act shall be shared with the Authority by the Ministry of Tourism within a maximum period of 1 (one) month from the date of commencement of this Act.\n(c) Information regarding tourist resorts, integrated tourist resorts, private islands, resort hotels, tourist vessels, tourist hotels, tourist guesthouses, and other such places registered under Law No. 2/99 (Maldives Tourism Act) after the commencement of this Act shall be shared with the Authority by the Ministry of Tourism within a maximum period of 1 (one) month from the date of registration of any such place.\n(d) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in any other law, the Registrar of Companies shall share with the Authority the information required by the Authority to enforce this Act.\n(e) Any information obtained by the Authority under paragraphs (a), (b), (c), and (d) of this Article shall not be used for any purpose other than to enforce this Act and to achieve the objectives of this Act.\n\n**Chapter Five**\n**Conversion of a Portion of Income Received in Foreign Currency to Rufiyaa**\n\n**Parties Required to Convert Income Received in Foreign Currency**\n9.\nThe parties who are required to fulfill the obligation to convert foreign currency, as stated in Article 10 of this Act, are set out below.\n(a) \"Category-A Tourism Establishment\": This category shall include tourist resorts, integrated tourist resorts, private islands, resort hotels, and other such places operating in the Maldives registered under Law No. 2/99 (Maldives Tourism Act).\n(b) \"Category-B Tourism Establishment\": This category shall include tourist vessels, tourist hotels, and tourist guesthouses registered under Law No. 2/99 (Maldives Tourism Act).\n(c) Parties, other than those mentioned in paragraphs (a) and (b) of this Article and financial institutions, who have received an amount equivalent to at least 15,000,000.00 (fifteen million) United States Dollars in foreign currency within the preceding calendar year for goods and services sold or provided by another party.\n\n**Conversion of a Portion of Income Received in Foreign Currency**\n10.\n(a) Category-A Tourism Establishments shall convert to Rufiyaa, to a bank, an amount of foreign currency determined in a manner chosen by the establishment from the following two methods, by the party operating the establishment.\n(1) The amount due for the total number of tourists who have visited the establishment within a calendar month at a rate of 500.00 (five hundred) United States Dollars per tourist; or\n(2) 20% (twenty percent) of the gross sales in foreign currency of the establishment within a calendar month.\n(b) Category-B Tourism Establishments shall convert to Rufiyaa, to a bank, an amount of foreign currency determined in a manner chosen by the establishment from the following two methods, by the party operating the establishment.\n(1) The amount due for the total number of tourists who have visited the establishment within a calendar month at a rate of 25 (twenty-five) United States Dollars per tourist; or\n(2) 20% (twenty percent) of the gross sales in foreign currency of the establishment within a calendar month.\n(c) The parties mentioned in paragraph (c) of Article 9 of this Act shall convert to Rufiyaa, to a bank, 20% (twenty percent) of the gross sales in foreign currency of the goods and services they sell or provide within a calendar month.\n(d) The money required to be converted to a bank for each calendar month under paragraphs (a), (b), and (c) of this Article shall be converted and finalized before the 28th (twenty-eighth) day of the third month following that month.\n\n**Parties and Circumstances Exempted from Foreign Currency Conversion**\n11.\n(a) For the purpose of sub-paragraph (1) of paragraph (a) of Article 10 of this Act and sub-paragraph (1) of paragraph (b) of that Article, the following parties shall not be included in calculating the number of tourists visiting a tourism establishment as stated in that Article.\n(1) Tourists who have not spent more than 24 (twenty-four) hours at the tourism establishment;\n(2) Children under the age of 12 (twelve) among the tourists;\n(3) Persons staying at the tourism establishment free of charge or on a complimentary basis;\n(4) Guests who have been granted special privileges by the Government.\n(b) Tourist vessels registered and operated outside the Maldives, from among the tourist vessels mentioned in paragraph (b) of Article 9 of this Act, shall be exempted from this Act.\n\n**Reviewing the Amount of Foreign Currency to be Converted**\n12.\n(a) After calculating the amount of foreign currency to be converted by the parties mentioned in Article 9 of this Act in accordance with Article 10 of this Act, if a party submits to the Authority stating that if they convert that amount of foreign currency, they will not have the required foreign currency to fulfill the following foreign currency obligation or obligations, and if the Authority is convinced that such an amount of foreign currency will not be available, the Authority may grant permission to convert a lesser amount than the amount stated in Article 10 of this Act for a period determined by the Authority.\n(1) Taxes payable in foreign currency and obligations payable to the government in foreign currency;\n(2) Debt payable in foreign currency to a foreign financial institution operating in or outside the Maldives;\n(3) Foreign currency obligations determined to be paid in a judgment or order of a court of law, or a decision of a tribunal, or a decision made under a dispute resolution mechanism such as arbitration; or\n(4) Other foreign currency obligations authorized by the Authority.\n(b) A request for the Authority\u0027s permission under paragraph (a) of this Article shall be submitted with the details of the foreign currency obligations to be fulfilled and other information and documents determined by the Authority.\n\n**Selling Converted Foreign Currency to the Authority**\n13.\n(a) A certain percentage, as determined by the Authority, of the foreign currency received by a bank under Article 10 of this Act shall be sold to the Authority by that bank within a period determined by the Authority.\n(b) The details of the foreign currency received by a bank within a month under Article 10 of this Act shall be submitted to the Authority by that bank within a period determined by the Authority and in a manner determined by the Authority.\n\n**Chapter Six**\n**Investigation and Action Against Parties Violating the Law**\n\n**Power to Investigate Matters of Parties Violating the Law**\n14.\n(a) The Authority is empowered to investigate and take action on matters of parties deemed to have violated this Act and the regulations made hereunder, matters of parties deemed to have falsified accounts and information in carrying out the requirements of this Act, and matters of parties who violate the orders issued by the Authority under this Act.\n(b) In investigating the matters looked into by the Authority as stated in paragraph (a) of this Article, the powers vested in the Authority and the procedures to be followed in investigating matters shall be stated in the regulations made under this Act.\n\n**Taking Action Against Parties Violating the Law**\n15.\n(a) Parties who do not transfer or deposit foreign currency into a foreign currency account opened in a bank as stated in Article 7 of this Act, and parties who do not deposit the specified amount, are subject to a fine by the Authority of an amount not exceeding 0.25% (zero point two five percent) of the foreign currency that party is required to deposit for that month. And, in imposing such a fine, if the Authority sees fit, it may determine to fine that party an amount not exceeding 0.25% (zero point two five percent) of the foreign currency required to be deposited for that month for each day that the violation is not rectified or the required actions are not taken.\n(b) Parties who do not convert foreign currency to Rufiyaa as stated in Article 10 of this Act, and parties who do not convert the specified amount, are subject to a fine by the Authority of an amount not exceeding 0.5% (zero point five percent) of the foreign currency that party is required to convert for that month. And, in imposing the fine, if the Authority sees fit, it may determine to fine that party an amount not exceeding 0.5% (zero point five percent) of the foreign currency required to be converted for that month for each day that the violation is not rectified or the required actions are not taken.\n(c) Except for the matters stated in paragraphs (a) and (b) of this Article, parties who violate this Act or a regulation made under this Act or an order issued by the Authority under this Act or a regulation made under this Act, are subject to a fine by the Authority of an amount between 10,000 (ten thousand) Rufiyaa and 1,000,000 (one million) Rufiyaa, based on the gravity of the act committed by that party.\n(d) In imposing a fine under paragraphs (a) and (b) of this Article, the Authority has the discretion to impose the fine in foreign currency.\n\n**Suspension of Licenses of Parties Who Do Not Pay Fines for a Specific Period**\n16.\nIf a party who has been fined by the Authority under this Act and has been instructed to pay the fine fails to pay the fine within 90 (ninety) days from the date the Authority instructed the payment of the fine, the Authority is empowered to instruct the relevant state institution to suspend the business licenses issued to that party by state institutions for a specific period, in a manner prescribed in the regulations made under this Act.\n\n**Collection of Fine Money**\n17.\n(a) In addition to taking action against a party who has been fined by the Authority under this Act and has failed to pay the fine as stated in Article 16 of this Act, the Authority is empowered to recover the fine money by submitting the matter of recovering the fine money to the court.\n(b) Before submitting the matter of a party who is required to pay a fine to the court as stated in paragraph (a) of this Article, the Authority is empowered to arrange for lenient ways for that party to pay the fine money, in a manner prescribed in the regulations made under this Act.\n(c) A matter submitted to the court under paragraph (a) of this Article shall be investigated and a decision on the matter shall be made by the court within a maximum period of 180 (one hundred and eighty) days from the date the matter is submitted.\n\n**Chapter Seven**\n**Miscellaneous**\n\n**Registration with the Authority**\n18.\n(a) Sellers of goods and providers of services in the tourism sector at the time of commencement of this Act shall submit an application for registration with the Authority within 10 (ten) days of the commencement of this Act.\n(b) Parties registered with the Authority for the purpose of Regulation No. 2024/R-91 (Foreign Exchange Regulation) at the time of commencement of this Act shall be considered as parties registered under paragraph (a) of this Article.\n(c) Parties who meet the requirements stated in sub-paragraph (2) of paragraph (a) of Article 7 of this Act at the time of commencement of this Act shall submit an application for registration with the Authority within 30 (thirty) days from the date of commencement of this Act.\n(d) Parties who commence providing a good or service in the tourism sector after the date of commencement of this Act shall submit an application for registration with the Authority within 30 (thirty) days from the date of commencement of the business.\n(e) From among the parties who commence a business other than sellers of goods or providers of services in the tourism sector and financial institutions after the date of commencement of this Act, parties who have received foreign currency equivalent to or more than 15,000,000.00 (fifteen million) United States Dollars for the goods sold and services provided by them by the end of a calendar year, shall submit an application for registration with the Authority before the end of January of the year following that calendar year.\n(f) The information and documents to be submitted for registration under this Article, and the procedures and formalities to be followed in applying for and carrying out registration shall be stated in the regulations made under this Act.\n\n**Submission of Information and Record Keeping**\n19.\n(a) In order to obtain the information required by the Authority under this Act or the regulations made under this Act, the parties who are required to comply with this Act shall submit the information, documents, and reports instructed by the Authority, in the manner and with the details instructed by the Authority.\n(b) The parties who are required to comply with this Act shall maintain the information and accounts determined by the Authority for a period determined by the Authority.\n(c) For the purpose of paragraph (b) of this Article, this Article does not preclude the keeping of records electronically.\n\n**Responsibilities and Powers of the Authority**\n20.\n(a) This Act shall be administered and enforced by the Authority.\n(b) In enforcing this Act, the Authority is empowered to do the following:\n(1) To formulate and implement the policies required to develop and maintain the foreign exchange market of the Maldives in an appropriate manner;\n(2) To formulate regulations, circulars, principles, instructions, orders, procedures, and guidelines for the enforcement and administration of this Act, and to monitor compliance with them;\n(3) To determine the transactions that can be conducted in foreign currency in the Maldives, including transactions made through bank accounts; and\n(4) To do all other things necessary to achieve the objectives of this Act or to administer and enforce this Act.\n\n**Confidentiality**\n21.\nExcept when required by a court of law in a legal matter, or in the performance of the duties or work obligations of the Authority that person holds, no member of the Board of the Authority or any person who has held membership of the Board or any employee or agent or consultant currently working or who has worked at the Authority shall disclose to any other party any information of any party obtained by the Authority under this Act.\n\n**Transitional Provisions**\n22.\n(a) The total realized sales proceeds in foreign currency received by sellers of goods and providers of services in the tourism sector in the months of October, November, and December of the year 2024 under paragraph (a) of Article 7 of Regulation No. 2024/R-91 (Foreign Exchange Regulation) shall be transferred or deposited into a foreign currency account opened in a bank as stated in that regulation.\n(b) For each tourist who has visited a Category-A Tourism Establishment as defined in Regulation No. 2024/R-91 (Foreign Exchange Regulation) in the months of October, November, and December of the year 2024, the party operating the establishment shall convert to Rufiyaa, to a bank, at the rate of 500.00 (five hundred) United States Dollars, in the manner stated in that regulation.\n(c) For each tourist who has visited a Category-B Tourism Establishment as defined in Regulation No. 2024/R-91 (Foreign Exchange Regulation) in the months of October, November, and December of the year 2024, the party operating the establishment shall convert to Rufiyaa, to a bank, at the rate of 25 (twenty-five) United States Dollars, in the manner stated in that regulation.\n(d) The submission of information required to be submitted to the Authority regarding the deposit and conversion of foreign currency and other matters as stated in Regulation No. 2024/R-91 (Foreign Exchange Regulation) shall continue as stated in that regulation until the matters under paragraphs (a), (b), and (c) of this Article are completed.\n(e) This Act does not preclude the application of regulations formulated and in effect under another relevant law prior to the commencement of this Act, in order to regulate and administer a specific matter stated in this Act, until a regulation concerning that matter is made and comes into effect under this Act, as long as such regulations do not contradict the principles and rules related to the matter stated in this Act.\n\n**Repealed Law and Regulation**\n23.\n(a) With the commencement of this Act, paragraphs (r) and (b) of Article 24 of Law No. 6/81 (Maldives Monetary Authority Act 1981) are repealed.\n(b) With the exception of the matters specified in paragraphs (a), (b), and (c) of Article 22 of this Act, Regulation No. 2024/R-91 (Foreign Exchange Regulation) is repealed upon the commencement of this Act.\n\n**Making and Administering Regulations**\n24.\n(a) The regulations to be made under this Act shall be made and administered by the Authority.\n(b) The regulations to be made under this Act shall be formulated by the Authority and published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives within 2 (two) months from the date of commencement of this Act.\n\n**Commencement of the Act**\n25.\nThis Act shall come into force on 1 January 2025.\n\n**Definitions**\n26.\nUnless the context in which a phrase or word is used in this Act clearly indicates a different meaning, the following phrases and words are given the meanings set out below in relation to those phrases and words.\n(a) \"Remittance service provider\" means a party licensed to provide remittance services under Law No. 8/2021 (National Payment System Act).\n(b) \"International transaction\" means a transaction of transferring foreign currency from the Maldives to abroad or from abroad to the Maldives.\n(c) \"Bank\" means any party licensed or permitted to conduct banking business or provide a banking service or carry out a banking activity as specified in Law No. 24/2010 (Maldives Banking Act).\n(d) \"Foreign currency\" means the currency of any country other than the Maldives.\n(e) \"Insurance company\" means a company licensed by the Authority to conduct insurance business in the Maldives.\n(f) \"Authority\" means the Maldives Monetary Authority established under Law No. 6/81 (Maldives Monetary Authority Act 1981).\n(g) \"Financing company\" means a company licensed by the Authority to conduct financing business in the Maldives.\n(h) \"Party\" includes a natural person and a legal person.\n(i) \"MIRA\" means the Maldives Inland Revenue Authority established under Law No. 3/2010 (Tax Administration Act).\n(j) \"Financial institution\" means a party licensed by the Maldives Monetary Authority or the Capital Market Development Authority.\n(k) \"Capital Market Development Authority\" means the Capital Market Development Authority established under Law No. 2/2006 (Maldives Financial Securities Act).\n(l) \"Goods and services of the tourism sector\" means the goods and services stated as goods and services of the tourism sector in Law No. 10/2011 (Goods and Services Tax Act).\n(m) \"Tourists\" means foreigners who come to the Maldives with a tourist visa.\n(n) \"A business that earns income in foreign currency\" means any business that earns income in foreign currency. In this regard, it is not necessary for a specific amount of income to be received in foreign currency. Even if any amount is received as income in foreign currency, it will be considered a business that earns income in foreign currency.\n(o) \"State institution\" means all institutions and offices operating under the executive branch, all institutions and offices operating under the legislative branch, all independent commissions and offices of independent posts established under the Constitution and the law, and all institutions and offices operating under them, and all institutions, offices, and places operating under the judicial branch.\n\nLaw Number: 32/2024\nDate of Commencement: 01 January 2025\n\nCopyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office",
